-- Ruble Retreats to Two-Week Low Against Dollar, Bonds Decline
-- B y   V l a d i m i r   K u z n e t s o v
-- 2013-11-01T10:12:23Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-01/ruble-retreats-to-two-week-low-against-dollar-bonds-decline.html
The ruble headed for a two-week low
and Russian bonds fell as speculation the Federal Reserve will
pare stimulus curbed appetite for riskier assets.  The Russian currency weakened 0.3 percent against the
dollar by 1:08 p.m. in Moscow, heading for a 1.4 percent decline
for the week. The yield on government bonds due February 2027
rose one basis point, or 0.01 percentage point, to 7.55 percent.  Emerging-market assets dropped after the Fed maintained $85
billion in monthly bond purchases on Oct. 30, while saying the
economy shows signs of “underlying strength.” An index of the
20 most-active emerging-country currencies fell for a fifth day,
losing 0.5 percent to 94.2215, data compiled by Bloomberg show.
Economists at Citigroup Inc. and Barclays Plc said the Fed
policy statement left open the possibility of reduced bond
purchases as soon as December.  “People are moving back to the dollar from emerging
currencies and the ruble is among them,” Anton Zakharov, money
manager at OAO Promsvyazbank in Moscow, said in e-mailed
comments. Investors are “expecting the tapering in the U.S. and
minding a complicated economic situation in  emerging markets ,”
he said.  Oil,  Russia ’s main export earner, gained 0.3 percent to
$109.17 a barrel in  London .  The ruble traded little changed against the euro at 43.7525
and weakened 0.2 percent  against the dollar-euro basket  Bank
Rossii uses to 37.3193.  To contact the reporter on this story:
